content.description: Start about 15' left of Chinos Arete. Clip a low first bolt and make boulder moves up onto the slopey ledge. Climb past two more bolts on great features and make a mantle that guards the two bolt chain anchor on the ledge.
Lower crux moves. Trust the feet. Work right past first bolt up to slopers, Trust the feet crank to the crimps. Super fun top.

At the far left end of the Outback Wall is Secret Agent. It starts just to the right of the ramp that leads to the top of the cliff. Climb up a thin technical section past 2 bolts. The climb gets easier the higher you go. Place gear in horizontal cracks and finish at a rap anchor.
Place gear down low in a horizontal break. Climb straight past 2 bolts to anchors. This climb has steep technical climbing on thin crimps, knobs, and horizontal breaks.
Start with hands in the horizontal crack, move up to a dish, then up to a diagonaling flake/rail thing and top out.
content.location: About 6ft left of Burn the Evidence, right in front of the first pine tree left of the gully. Walk off to the left.

content.description: The most righthand route on the cliff. Climb up on pockets to a bolt. Continue up making slab moves to a horizontal (place cam or tricam). Continue up past 2 more bolts to a rap anchor. The crux is at the top.

Climb the route to the right of Secret Agent. Climb straight up past 3 bolts. Continue up placing a cam on mellow climbing or go right to the rap anchors. A great safe route to get a feel for the climbing in The Outback.
The testpiece at The Outback. Climb up near vertical rock on thin technical moves. The crux is from bolt 2-4. Pull the small roof at the fourth bolt to rap anchors.
Start with some pockets and move up past a couple horizontals to a thin top out. A fall could be scary.
content.location: A clean streak of rock straight up located in the Outback to the left of Secret Agent. It starts right at the top of "Dead mans gully".

content.description: Crouching match start on flat horizontal then throw for a good pocket. Now move to horizontal crack that runs the length of the traverse. Catch a small rest after about 20 ft then go for the crux section, about 20 ft of super pumpy moves before another good rest. Then finish up Dead Mans Drop.
content.protection: You might want a pad/spotter if you choose to top out, but you're never more than a couple feet off the ground except for the finish.
content.location: This is located on the far left, upperside of the Outback wall. Right near where the band ends on the far left, there is a flat horizontal hold 3-4 feet off the ground. Walk off left from the top.

content.description: The crux is at the first bolt.Clip the bolt low and pull up on a sloping crimp and shoot for a side pull up left.This route is a change of pace from the rest of the routes here because there are no flaring horizontals.The routes name came from the effort from the chino's.
content.protection: Two well placed bolt and optional gear down low, up to the pine tree.
content.location: The route starts on the right side of the Outback wall.Around the cornner You will see the obvious start.

content.description: Start by moving up to horizontal crack pockets, make a big move to a slopey dish, stand up and mantle the insecure round top out.
content.location: This is immediately left of Dead Mans Drop on the Outback wall. It's very close to "DMD", but is completely indepndent and has a MUCH safer landing. Walk off to climbers left.

pathTokens: New Durham Area  (Longstack, Devil's Den, Rines Hill, etc.)

content.description: The Outback Wall is the most popular of all the cliffs. Great face climbing with some of the best routes on it.
